3. Preparing uranyl formate solution (0.75%) for negative stain EM. The detailed protocol was described previously 5
Weigh out 37.5mg of uranyl formate into a small beaker;
Add 5 ml of boiling water and stir for 5 minutes in the dark;
Add 10μl 5M NaOH, continue stir for 5 minutes;
Filter the solution using a syringe filter (Fisherbrand, 13mm syringe filter, 0.2μm, Nylon non-sterile, catalog number 09-720-5), and store the filtered solution in a 8ml Falcon tube covered with aluminum foil;
Note. Uranyl Formate powder can be purchased from Electron Microscopy Sciences (Hatfield, PA), catalog number 22451. Uranyl formate solution is light sensitive and should be kept away from direct light, for example by covering the Falcon tube with aluminum foil. A freshly prepared solution has a light yellow color (Fig. 3A). Stain solution can be kept on the bench for one to two weeks before it starts precipitating. Uranyl formate is acidic with a pH ~4. Adding NaOH increases the pH, but adding it too quickly or in excess can cause the stain to precipitate. In addition to generating contrast, uranyl formate also fixes the protein sample. Because the fixation rate is so rapid, the low pH usually does not affect the overall protein conformations or protein complex formation 7.
4. Protocol for preparing negative stain EM grid. This protocol was described in detail previously 5
Glow-discharge carbon coated grid, using PELCO easiGlow GlowDischarge system (Ted Pella Inc., USA). The current used is 15 mA and grids are glow discharged for 30 sec. Note. Glow-discharged grids should be used shortly after glow discharging. We often use the grids in less than 2 hours after the glow discharge.
Place two 20μl drops of distilled water and two 25μl drops of uranyl formate solution on a piece of parafilm (Fig. 3B).
